  "note_id": "RA_EN_029",
  "language": "en",
  "module1": {
    "clean_text": "A [AGE] girl was seen at The Department of Neurosurgery, Yuquan Hospital, Tsinghua University (Beijing, China) with a three-year history of episodic convulsions accompanied by loss of consciousness and worsening symptoms. The seizures primarily included absence seizures and generalized tonic-clonic seizures. The main clinical presentation involved a sudden bowing motion (slightly forwards and downwards, to the left) occurring either singly or in clusters. Occasionally, the body would slowly dip to the left and then to the right while the upper and lower limbs became stiff, indicative of absence seizures. These episodes lasted for about half a minute, not exceeding one minute, before subsiding. Oral medications such as oxcarbazepine, clonazepam, topiramate, and valproate provided limited symptom control, with seizure episodes occurring 4–10 times per month. There was no prior history of difficult birth, lack of oxygen, encephalitis, or any other medical conditions. Written informed consent was obtained from the patient’s family.",
    "phi_map": {
      "AGE": "seven-year-old"
    },
